<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Sauvignon Blanc's Acidity to Cut Through Rich Foods</strong> - Sauvignon Blanc's naturally high acidity (typically 6-8 g/L) makes it exceptional with fatty fish like salmon, creamy goat cheese, and rich avocado dishes. The wine's tartaric and malic acids literally cleanse the palate between bites, preventing flavor fatigue. Loire Valley Sancerre works brilliantly with chèvre because both share the same limestone terroir influence.</li>

  <li><strong>Temperature Control is Critical for Food Harmony</strong> - Serve Sauvignon Blanc at exactly 45-50°F (7-10°C) for food pairings. Too cold (below 45°F) and you'll miss the wine's aromatic compounds like 3-mercapto-3-methylbutanol that complement herbs and vegetables. Too warm (above 55°F) and the alcohol becomes prominent, overwhelming delicate seafood and salads.</li>

  <li><strong>Leverage Pyrazine Compounds for Herb-Forward Dishes</strong> - Sauvignon Blanc's signature "green" flavors come from methoxypyrazines, the same compounds found in bell peppers, jalapeños, and fresh herbs. Pair New Zealand Sauvignon Blanc (highest pyrazine levels) with herb-crusted fish, pesto dishes, or green vegetable preparations where these flavors create perfect aromatic synergy.</li>

  <li><strong>Regional Terroir Dictates Ideal Food Partners</strong> - Match wine origin to cuisine style: Sancerre's mineral-driven profile pairs with oysters and sushi; Marlborough's tropical fruit notes complement Thai and Vietnamese cuisine; Austrian Sauvignon Blanc's white pepper notes work with European dishes featuring similar spicing.</li>

  <li><strong>Avoid Decanting - Preserve Volatile Aromatics</strong> - Never decant Sauvignon Blanc before food service. The wine's most food-friendly aromatics (thiols, esters) are highly volatile and dissipate quickly when exposed to air. Pour directly from bottle to preserve the fresh, bright character that makes food combinations sing.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Larger Bowled Glasses for Complex Food Pairings</strong> - While Sauvignon Blanc is often served in narrow flutes, use a medium-bowled white wine glass (8-10 oz capacity) when pairing with food. The increased surface area releases more aromatic compounds, enhancing the wine's ability to complement complex dishes with multiple ingredients.</li>

  <li><strong>Timing Matters - Drink Young for Optimal Food Synergy</strong> - Most Sauvignon Blancs are designed for immediate consumption within 2-3 years of vintage. The fresh acidity and vibrant fruit flavors that make excellent food pairings diminish with age as the wine develops tertiary aromas that can conflict with delicate preparations.</li>

  <li><strong>Consider Residual Sugar Levels for Spicy Cuisine</strong> - For Asian dishes with heat and spice, choose Sauvignon Blancs with 2-4 g/L residual sugar (like some German examples) rather than bone-dry versions. The slight sweetness tempers spice while the acidity maintains freshness, creating better balance than completely dry wines with fiery foods.</li>
</ol>



