    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing Loire Valley versus New Zealand Sauvignon Blanc with food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Loire Valley Sauvignon Blancs like Sancerre offer more mineral-driven, restrained profiles that pair excellently with oysters, chèvre, and delicate fish preparations. New Zealand versions display intense tropical fruit and herbaceous notes that complement bolder flavors like Thai cuisine, grilled vegetables, and dishes with cilantro or jalapeños. The Loire's subtlety works with refined cuisine, while New Zealand's intensity matches more assertive flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can Sauvignon Blanc handle spicy foods, and which styles work best?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sauvignon Blanc can handle moderate spice levels, particularly with Asian cuisines featuring fresh herbs and citrus-based heat. New Zealand and South African styles with their tropical fruit intensity best complement dishes with jalapeño, green curry, or Vietnamese pho. However, avoid pairing with extremely spicy dishes or those heavy in chili powder, as the wine's acidity can amplify the heat sensation rather than cooling it.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve Sauvignon Blanc at different temperatures depending on the food pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, temperature adjustments can optimize food pairings with Sauvignon Blanc. Serve at 45-48°F for delicate seafood and salads to preserve the wine's crisp acidity and bright fruit. For heartier pairings like grilled vegetables or herb-crusted chicken, serve slightly warmer at 50-52°F to allow more complexity and texture to emerge. Never serve above 55°F, as the wine loses its refreshing quality that makes it such an excellent food wine.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What vegetables pair best with Sauvignon Blanc, and how should they be prepared?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Asparagus is the classic match, especially when grilled or roasted to concentrate its flavors and complement the wine's herbaceous notes. Green vegetables like snap peas, green beans, and Brussels sprouts work excellently, particularly when prepared with lemon, herbs, or light vinaigrettes. Bell peppers, zucchini, and fennel also pair beautifully, but avoid heavy cream or butter-based preparations that can overwhelm the wine's delicate profile.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Sauvignon Blanc good for wine pairing beginners, and what are foolproof combinations?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sauvignon Blanc is excellent for pairing beginners due to its high acidity and bright flavors that complement rather than compete with food. Start with foolproof combinations like goat cheese and crackers, grilled shrimp with lemon, or a simple green salad with vinaigrette. The wine's forgiving nature means it pairs well with most light, fresh dishes, making it difficult to create truly bad combinations when following the basic principle of matching intensity levels.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What cheese pairings work best with Sauvignon Blanc beyond goat cheese?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While chèvre is the classic pairing, Sauvignon Blanc also excels with fresh mozzarella, feta, and young pecorino due to their bright acidity and mild flavors. Gruyère and aged cheddar can work with more complex, oak-aged versions of the wine. Avoid strongly aged cheeses like Roquefort or Camembert, as their intensity can overwhelm Sauvignon Blanc's delicate fruit characteristics and create unpleasant metallic notes.</p>
